PART 2Trailers
	Trailer registration
		Trailer registration
			Regulations may provide for the compulsory or voluntary registration oftrailers kept or used on roads in a register kept by the Secretary of State.
			The regulations may—
				require or permit the keeper of a trailer to apply to the Secretary ofState for its registration;
				make provision about the procedure for applications;
				make provision for the purpose of ensuring that each registered trailer hasa number which is recorded in the register;
				make provision about the form of the register and the information to beincluded in it;
				provide for the giving of registration documents;
				provide for the transfer, surrender or production of registrationdocuments;
				provide for the expiry of registration documents;
				require the destruction of a registration document in specifiedcircumstances;
				make other provision in connection with—
				the registration of a trailer,
				the transfer of a registered trailer to a new keeper,
				the accuracy of information included in the register, or
				the enforcement of provisions of the regulations.
			In this Part—
				  * “motor vehicle” means a mechanically-propelled vehicle which is intended or adapted for use on roads; 
				  * “trailer” means anything on wheels which is intended or adapted to be drawn by a motor vehicle; 
				  * “regulations” means regulations made by the Secretary of State. 
		Inspections and information
			Regulations may, in connection with any provision of regulations undersection 13—
				provide for the inspection of trailers or registration documents byexaminers or stopping officers, or
				require a person to provide information or things to the Secretary of Stateor another person, or to make declarations.
			Regulations under subsection (1)(a) may, in particular, make provisionabout—
				notification of inspections;
				inspection of a trailer in the absence of its owner or keeper;
				certificates as to the outcome of inspections;
				record-keeping in relation to inspections;
				the giving of duplicates or copies of certificates.
			In this section—
				  * “examiner” means— 
				an examiner appointed under section 66A of the Road Traffic Act 1988, or
				an examiner appointed under Article 74 of the [Road Traffic (Northern Ireland)Order 1995 (S.I. 1995/2994 (N.I. 18)](/id/nisi/1995/2994?view=plain "Go toitem of legislation"));
					  * “stopping officer” means an officer appointed under section 66B of the Road Traffic Act 1988. 
		Registration marks and registration plates
			Regulations may require or authorise the Secretary of State, whenregistering a trailer, to assign a mark (a “registration mark”) to thetrailer.
			Regulations under subsection (1) may make further provision about theassignment of registration marks, for example, provision authorising theSecretary of State to—
				assign a registration mark to a trailer to which another registration markhas previously been assigned;
				assign to a trailer (on its first registration or later) a registrationmark previously assigned to another trailer;
				withdraw a registration mark for the time being assigned to a trailer;
				re-assign to a trailer a registration mark previously assigned to it butsubsequently withdrawn.
			Regulations may prohibit a person from keeping or using a registeredtrailer unless a plate displaying the registration mark assigned to thetrailer (a “registration plate”) is fixed on it.
			Regulations under subsection (3) may—
				specify the size, shape, material of manufacture or other characteristicsof a registration plate;
				specify the size, shape and character of a registration mark;
				make provision for the purpose of ensuring that registration marks areeasily distinguishable (by day or by night);
				make other provision about—
				the display of registration marks, or
				the fixing of registration plates.
			Regulations may prohibit a person from keeping or using a trailer on a roadwhere a plate fixed on the trailer displays a mark which—
				is not assigned to the trailer under regulations under subsection (1), and
				is of a size, shape and character specified in regulations made by virtueof subsection (4)(b).
			Regulations may permit or require registration plates to contain or displayinformation other than registration marks.
			In this section “plate” includes any other device.
		Marking of trailers
			Regulations may make provision for the marking of registered trailers(otherwise than under section 15) or of trailers in respect of which anapplication for registration has been made.
			The regulations may include provision—
				as to the persons by whom and the times at which trailers are to be marked;
				as to the form of any mark and the manner and position in which it is to bemade;
				requiring information about marks made under the regulations to be providedto the Secretary of State.
		Fees 
			Regulations may authorise the Secretary of State to charge a fee of aspecified amount in respect of—
				the registration of a trailer;
				the giving of registration documents;
				the inspection of a trailer;
				the giving of a certificate as to the outcome of an inspection of atrailer;
				the correction of an error in such a certificate;
				the giving of a duplicate of such a certificate.
			The regulations may—
				provide that anything for which a fee is payable is conditional on paymentof the fee;
				make provision about repayment of fees charged under the regulations,including provision—
				that repayment is to be made only if a specified person is satisfied thatspecified conditions are met or in other specified circumstances;
				that only partial repayment is to be made;
				specifying the amount of any partial repayment, or providing for themanner in which that amount is to be determined.
		Offences 
			Regulations may create offences relating to—
				keeping or using an unregistered or incorrectly registered trailer on aroad;
				the breach of a specified provision of regulations under any of sections 13to 17;
				obscuring a registration mark, or causing or allowing a registration markto become not easily distinguishable;
				the provision of false or misleading information, documents or declarationsunder regulations under any of sections 13 to 17;
				the keeping or use of a trailer whose registration document has expiredwithout being replaced;
				obstructing a person carrying out an inspection of a trailer;
				pretending to be entitled to carry out inspections of trailers.
			If regulations under subsection (1)(a) create an offence of keeping orusing an incorrectly registered trailer on a road, the regulations mustprovide for it to be a defence for a person charged with the offence to prove—
				that there was no reasonable opportunity, before the material time, toprovide information to the Secretary of State for the purpose of correctingthe register, or
				that the person had reasonable grounds for believing, or that it wasreasonable for the person to expect, that the trailer was correctlyregistered.
			Regulations may—
				require a person to provide information to a specified person on requestabout the identity of someone who is alleged to have committed an offenceunder regulations under subsection (1)(a), (b) or (c), and
				provide for it to be an offence to fail to provide the information.
			Regulations under subsection (3)(b) must provide for it to be a defence toprove that the person did not know, and could not with reasonable diligencehave ascertained, the identity of the person concerned.
			Regulations may—
				authorise a court to accept as evidence (or, in Scotland, sufficientevidence) that a person is someone alleged to have committed an offence underregulations under subsection (1)(a), (b) or (c), any admission of that factwhich is proved to have been made by the person in information provided underregulations under subsection (3)(a), and
				make provision as to the manner in which it is to be proved that anadmission was made in information provided under regulations under subsection(3)(a).
			Regulations under this section which create an offence must provide for theoffence to be triable only summarily.
			Regulations under this section may not provide for an offence to bepunishable with imprisonment or with a fine exceeding level 3 on the standardscale.
			For the purposes of this section a trailer is “incorrectly registered” if—
				the register kept under regulations under section 13 does not include allof the information relating to the trailer that is required by regulationsunder section 13(2)(d), or
				the information relating to the trailer that is included in that registerincludes any incorrect information.
		Records 
			Regulations may provide for records maintained by the Secretary of State inconnection with the Secretary of State’s functions under regulations under anyof sections 13 to 17 to be admissible in proceedings as evidence (or, inScotland, sufficient evidence) of facts stated in them, subject to specifiedconditions as to authentication and any other specified conditions.
			For the purposes of this section “records” includes—
				a copy of any records, and
				a note or other representation of any information contained in records.
	Trailer safety
		Trailer safety: report
			The Secretary of State must prepare a report on the number and causes ofroad traffic accidents occurring in England, Wales or Scotland during thereporting period which—
				involved trailers, and
				caused injury or death to any person.
			The report must contain an assessment of whether—
				regulations under section 13 should provide for the compulsory registrationof relevant trailers;
				regulations under section 21 should be made.
			The report must be laid before Parliament within the period of one yearbeginning with the day on which this section comes into force.
			In this section—
				  * “relevant trailers” means trailers which are kept or used on roads and— 
				if constructed or adapted to carry a load, weigh more than 750 kilograms whenladen with the heaviest such load;
				otherwise, weigh more than 750 kilograms;
					  * “reporting period” means a period determined by the Secretary of State, which must be a continuous period of at least 12 months ending no earlier than 18 months before the day on which this section comes into force. 
		Trailer safety: testing regulations
			Regulations may provide for periodic testing of the construction, conditionor safety of relevant trailers.
			The regulations may amend provision made by or under Part 2 of the RoadTraffic Act 1988.
			The regulations may, in making consequential or other provision asmentioned in section 25(1)(a), amend any Act (whenever passed or made).
			No regulations under this section may be made before the report is laidbefore Parliament under section 20.
			In this section, “relevant trailers” has the meaning given by section20(4).
	Supplementary and interpretation
		Supplementary and interpretation
			The provision made by regulations under this Part may be limited in any wayprovided for by the regulations, for example—
				to trailers of a specified description;
				to trailers kept or used in specified circumstances;
				to trailers kept or used by a person of a specified description.
			In this Part—
				  * “inspection”, in relation to a trailer, means an inspection under regulations under section 14(1)(a); 
				  * “registered trailer” means a trailer registered under regulations under section 13; 
				  * “registration”, in relation to a trailer, means registration under regulations under section 13; 
				  * “registration document” means a registration document given in accordance with regulations under section 13(2)(e); 
				  * “registration mark” has the meaning given by section 15(1); 
				  * “regulations” has the meaning given by section 13(3); 
				  * “road”— 
				in relation to a trailer kept or used in England, Wales or Scotland, has themeaning given by section 192(1) of the Road Traffic Act 1988;
				in relation to a trailer kept or used in Northern Ireland, has the meaninggiven by Article 2(1) of the [Road Traffic (Northern Ireland) Order 1981 (S.I.1981/154 (N.I. 1)](/id/nisi/1981/154?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"));
					  * “specified” means specified in regulations; 
					  * “trailer” has the meaning given by section 13(3).
